text: When John Lasseter denied claims of these movies being crap with the simple fact that they were commercially successful I died a little bit inside. I mean seriously, as a huge fan of his work at Disney and Pixar alike it is a huge disappointment to see him fully blinded by this. Howthe hell does something being commercially successfully equals good? We've seen time to time that even the worst pieces of garbage Hollywood spews nowadays can churn lots of cash for all the wrong reasons (I'm looking at you transformers). That's not something to be proud of. That's not even the way a filmmaker should think.  He claims that he makes these films for the children that fall in love with his work. But John buddy children will fall in love with anything mildly successful and they'll move on to the next thing. This isn't like the masterpieces you've made that are everlasting. There's a difference. Worst of all it's a really contradicting ideology when Brad Bird and Andrew Stanton in past seminars and interviews claimed that they never made films just for kids. They're for everyone, so where's this bullshit of "I make movies for that little boy who loves the characters"come from? That's only 50% of what it should be about.
author: Fractorification

text: The car franchise is from the Disney Pixar Studio. The Planes movies are from Disney Toon Studios. Disney Animation Studios and Disney Pixar are the studios that create the more popular Disney Movies. Disney Toon Studios usually creates sequals or direct to video/dvd films. Such as Jungle book 2, Mulan 2, Atlantis 2, Little Mermaid 2 The Tinkerbell movies and many more. Example: Lion King is from Disney Animation Studios, Lion King 2 is from Disney Toon. You can tell from the different styles.
author: TigerTunes13

text: @MAjaMantras Movies like Aladdin and The Lion King are all 2D animation. Which means each slide is hand drawn. Movies like Tangled, Frozen and those from Pixar are all 3D animation which means most of it is done by computer. Disney is working to make movies with more 3D animation while leaving 2D for cartoons on tv. The last 2D movie was The Princess and the Frog. But it didn't get the results Disney hoped for. Sadly the 2D animation Era for Disney movies is ending or perhaps has already ended.
